The '''hair-crested drongo''' ('''''Dicrurus hottentottus''''') is an [[Asia]]n [[bird]] of the family [[Dicruridae]]. This species was formerly considered conspecific with ''[[Dicrurus bracteatus]]'', for which the name '''"spangled drongo"''' &ndash; formerly used for both &ndash; is now usually reserved.  Some authorities include the [[Sumatran drongo]] (''D. sumatranus'') in ''D. hottentottus'' as [[subspecies]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Lepage | first = Denis | year = 2003 | title = Spangled Drongo (''Dicrurus hottentottus'') | work = Avibase - The World Bird Database | url = http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&id=5E3DAB3851EFE922&ts=1239341506107&sec=summary | access-date = 2009-04-10}}  See also this [http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&id=89989E739886452B&ts=1239341967888&sec=summary more specific page].</ref>

It is native from [[Pakistan]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Berryman, Eaton, Loseby, Pop, Rheindt, Roddis, Tizzard |date=December 2021 |title=BirdingASIA, New and interesting avifaunal records for Pakistan, 2013–2021 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/358574615 |url-access= |archive-url= |archive-date=}}</ref> [[Bangladesh]],<ref name="iucn status 19 November 2021" /> [[India]], and [[Bhutan]] through [[Indochina]] to [[China]], [[Indonesia]], and [[Brunei]].<ref name="iucn status 19 November 2021" /> Hair-crested drongos move in small flocks and are very noisy. The "spangled drongo",  ''[[Dicrurus bracteatus]]'', is native on the east coast of Australia and its name is pejorative slang for a silly person. This may be due to its strange chattering and cackling.<ref>''Complete Book of Australian Birds'', Reader's Digest. 1977.</ref>

==Taxonomy==
In 1760, French zoologist [[Mathurin Jacques Brisson]] included a description of the hair-crested drongo in his ''Ornithologie'' based on a specimen that he mistakenly believed had been collected from the [[Cape of Good Hope]] in South Africa. He used the French name ''Le choucas du Cap de Bonne Espérance'' and the Latin ''Monedula Capitis Bonae Spei''.<ref name=brisson>{{ cite book | last=Brisson | first=Mathurin Jacques | author-link=Mathurin Jacques Brisson | year=1760 | title=Ornithologie, ou, Méthode contenant la division des oiseaux en ordres, sections, genres, especes & leurs variétés | volume=2 | language=French, Latin | place=Paris | publisher=Jean-Baptiste Bauche | pages=33–34, Plate 2 fig 2 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/36011205 }} The two stars (**) at the start of the section indicates that Brisson based his description on the examination of a specimen.</ref> Although Brisson coined Latin names, these do not conform to the [[binomial nomenclature|binomial system]] and are not recognised by the [[International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature]].<ref name=allen>{{cite journal |last=Allen | first=J.A. | author-link=Joel Asaph Allen | year=1910 | title=Collation of Brisson's genera of birds with those of Linnaeus |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=28 | pages=317–335 | hdl=2246/678 }}</ref> When in 1766, Swedish naturalist [[Carl Linnaeus]] updated his ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' for the [[12th edition of Systema Naturae|12th edition]], he added 240 species that had been previously described by Brisson.<ref name=allen/> One of these was the hair-crested drongo. Linnaeus included a brief description, coined the [[binomial name]] ''Corvus hottentottus'' and cited Brisson's work.<ref>{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=Carl | author-link=Carl Linnaeus | year=1766 | title=Systema naturae: per regna tria natura, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis | edition=12th | volume=1, Part 1 | publisher=Laurentii Salvii  | place=Holmiae (Stockholm) | language=Latin | page=155 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42946351 }}</ref> The [[type locality (biology)|type locality]] was subsequently corrected to Chandannagar in [[West Bengal]].<ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr  | editor2-last=Greenway | editor2-first=James C. Jr | year=1962 | title=Check-list of birds of the world | volume=15 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=152 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14485525 }}</ref> The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''hottentottus'' is from "Hottentot", a term formerly used for the [[Khoikhoi]], a nomadic pastoral people of southwest Africa.<ref name=hbwkey>{{cite web | last=Jobling | first=J.A. | year=2018 | title= Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/definition/hotentotta-hottentota-hottentotta-hottentottus | access-date=20 June 2018 }}</ref> This species is now placed in the [[genus]] ''[[Dicrurus]]'' that was introduced for the drongos by French ornithologist [[Louis Pierre Vieillot]] in 1816.<ref>{{cite book | last=Vieillot  | first=Louis Pierre | author-link=Louis Pierre Vieillot | title=Analyse d'une Nouvelle Ornithologie Élémentaire | publisher=Deterville/self | year=1816 | location=Paris | page = 41 | language=French| url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k9745205x/f47.image }}<!--BHL has a scan of an 1883 reprint  - same pagination http://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/12830237 --></ref>

Twelve [[subspecies]] are currently recognised, although some have been proposed as separate species:<ref name=ioc>{{BioRef|IOC |family=|access-date=31 August 2020}}</ref><ref name=Eaton2016>{{cite book |last1=Eaton |first1=JA |first2=B |last2=van Balen |first3=NW |last3=Brickle |first4=FE |last4=Rheindt |year=2016 |title=Birds of the Indonesian Archipelago. Greater Sundas and Wallacea. |publisher=Lynx Edicions, Barcelona}}</ref>

*''D. h. hottentottus'' {{small|(Linnaeus, 1766)}}	&ndash; [[India]], central Myanmar and southern Indochina	
*''D. h. brevirostris'' {{small|(Cabanis, 1851)}}	&ndash; central and southern [China, northern [[Myanmar]], and northern [[Indochina]]
*''D. h. borneensis'' {{small|(Sharpe, 1879)}} (Bornean spangled drongo) &ndash; [[Borneo]] and [[Maratua Island]]{{efn|name=species|Proposed as separate species<ref name=ioc/><ref name=Eaton2016/>}}
*''D. h. guillemardi'' {{small|(Salvadori, 1890)}}	(Obi spangled drongo) &ndash; [[Obi Islands]], North Maluku{{efn|name=species}}		
*''D. h. pectoralis'' {{small|Wallace, 1863}} (Sula spangled drongo) &ndash; [[Sula Island]], Philippines{{efn|name=species}}
*''D. h. suluensis'' {{small|Hartert, 1902}} (Sulu spangled drongo)	&ndash; [[Sulu Archipelago]], southwest Philippines{{efn|name=species}}
*''D. h. viridinitens'' {{small|(Salvadori, 1894)}}	(Mentawai Spangled Drongo) &ndash; [[Mentawai Islands Regency|Mentawai Islands]], western Sumatra;{{efn|name=species}}
*''D. h. banggaiensis'' {{small|Vaurie, 1952}}	&ndash; [[Banggai Islands Regency|Banggai Islands]], eastern Sulawesi;{{efn|name=white-eyed|It has been proposed to recognise ''leucops'' and ''banggaiensis'' as a separate species, the white-eyed spangled drongo<ref name=ioc/><ref name=Eaton2016/>}}
*''D. h. leucops'' {{small|Wallace, 1865}}	&ndash; [[Sulawesi]] and nearby islands;{{efn|name=white-eyed}}
*''D. h. faberi'' {{small|Hoogerwerf, 1962}}	&ndash; [[Panaitan|Panaitan Island]] in western [[Java]]{{efn|name=Javan|It has been proposed to recognise ''faberi'', ''jentincki'' and ''termeuleni'' as a separate species, the Javan spangled drongo.<ref name=ioc/><ref name=Eaton2016/>}}
*''D. h. jentincki'' {{small|(Vorderman, 1893)}} &ndash; [[Bali]], eastern [[Java]] and some islands in the [[Java Sea]]{{efn|name=Javan}}
*''D. h. termeuleni'' {{small|(Finsch, 1907)}}	&ndash;  [[Seribu Islands]] and islands in Jakarta Bay, northern Java{{efn|name=Javan}}

Notes:
{{Notelist}}

Several other former subspecies are now recognised as separate species or subspecies of other species in the species complex, the [[Tablas drongo]]	(''Dicrurus menagei'') and the [[Palawan drongo]] (''Dicrurus palawanensis'', including subspecies ''cuyensis'').

